@node MAIN "µls Manual"
                                     
                                  µls 1.3
                                     
                             by Matteo Cortese
                                     
   µls  (ie  micro-ls)  is a fast and optimized alternative to the beloved
 Dir  and  list commands.  It has been speficically designed for ergonomy,
 with the shell-user in mind.
   



 @{" Introduction " link INTRODUCTION}
 @{" Distribution " link DISTRIBUTION}
 @{" Requirements & installation " link REQUIREMENTS_&_INSTALLATION}
 @{" Usage " link USAGE}
 @{" Notes " link NOTES}
@endnode
@node INTRODUCTION "Introduction"
   
   µls  is  inspired by the UNIX command "ls",  but has features which are
 peculiar  to the Amiga philosophy,  in the first place the modest size of
 the executable, its ability to be made resident and the speed of use.  On
 the  other  hand,   µls inherits from the UNIX world the ease of combinig
 options  together,   as it supports those "-ldx..." switches UNIX wizards
 love  so  much.   So  I  am proud to say that µls takes "The best of both
 worlds".
   
   You want a list of µls's features, don't you? So here it is:
 
 - Two   formats   are   available:    @{" short format " link SHORT_FORMAT}  (multicolumn)  and
     @{" long format " link LONG_FORMAT}. (one file per line).
 
 - Everything is alphabetically sorted and dirs always come before files.
 
 - Dirs  can  be  shown  in white,  to emulate the "visual impact" of file
     requesters.
 
 - µls can adapt its output to the current console width.
 
 - You  can tell the type (dir,  link...) of each entry from the @{" suffix " link SUFFIX}
     appended to the entry's name.
 
 - You  can hide or filter out some files.  By default µls hides icons and
     backups.
 
 - You can use wildcards.
 
 - You  can  use  both  Amiga  (template)  and  UNIX  style (eg "-ld") for
     options.
 
 - For  every  XPK-compressed files,  µls shows packed and unpacked sizes,
     method and whether a password is required.
 
 - µls is pure and quick.
 
   
@endnode
